db.md — Third-party notices

This file lists third-party software included in or relied on by the
db.md reference toolkit (`crates/dbmd-core` + `crates/dbmd-cli`, building
the single `dbmd` binary), with their licenses.

Dependency licensing policy (enforced): permissive only. The allowlist of
accepted SPDX license identifiers is:

    MIT, Apache-2.0, BSD-3-Clause, 0BSD, Unlicense, Zlib,
    Unicode-3.0, ISC, CDLA-Permissive-2.0

No GPL, no AGPL, no LGPL-static. Zero AI/LLM dependencies — no provider
SDKs, no API keys, no model calls, no embeddings/vector/ANN crates of any
kind. Ripgrep is embedded via the `grep` + `ignore` libraries (no bundled
`rg` binary, no shelling out). The toolkit never phones home on its own (no
telemetry, no auto-update): the only network I/O is the link.md client verbs
(`dbmd resolve/sync/grant/propose/subscribe`), which run only when explicitly
invoked against a hub the user configured, over the TLS stack recorded below.

This policy is mechanically enforced by TWO gates over the whole resolved
tree, not by hand-maintaining this prose:

1. `cargo deny check licenses bans` against `/deny.toml` (repo root), wired
   into CI on every PR via `.github/workflows/licenses.yml`. `deny.toml`
   carries the allowlist above and a banned-crate list (the AI/LLM provider
   SDKs, every embeddings/vector/ANN crate, and any bundled `ripgrep`
   binary), so a forbidden license OR a forbidden crate fails the build.
2. The `license_policy` test in `crates/dbmd-cli/tests/license_policy.rs`,
   run by `cargo test`: it walks the *shipped* (normal-edge) dependency
   closure of the `dbmd` binary via `cargo metadata` and fails if any
   crate's SPDX expression cannot be satisfied entirely from the allowlist
   above (correct `AND`/`OR` semantics — a conjunctive term that is not on
   the list, e.g. a copyleft `AND`, fails the build). Build/dev-only and
   platform-foreign crates (Windows/wasm/etc.) are excluded because they do
   not ship in the released Linux/macOS binary. This test also asserts its
   allowlist is byte-identical to `deny.toml`'s, so the two gates can never
   silently disagree.

Re-run either gate after any dependency change; together they are the
source of truth, this prose is the summary. Adding a dependency under any
license not on the allowlist fails BOTH until the license is reviewed and
added to `deny.toml` AND the test — and recorded in this file.

Seven shipped crates carry an obligation beyond plain MIT/Apache and so are
called out explicitly (all remain permissive and on the allowlist):

- unicode-ident  (MIT OR Apache-2.0) AND Unicode-3.0
    The `Unicode-3.0` term is CONJUNCTIVE — it cannot be opted out of by
    choosing MIT or Apache, so the Unicode License v3 (a permissive
    attribution license) always binds. The crate ships a separate
    LICENSE-UNICODE file. Pulled in transitively by proc-macro2 / quote /
    syn (the proc-macro toolchain behind serde_derive, clap_derive,
    thiserror-impl), whose generated code is compiled into `dbmd`.
- encoding_rs    (Apache-2.0 OR MIT) AND BSD-3-Clause
    The `BSD-3-Clause` term is CONJUNCTIVE and always binds (covering the
    bundled WHATWG encoding tables). BSD-3-Clause is on the allowlist.
    Pulled in transitively under html2text (HTML/EPUB -> text).
- zlib-rs        Zlib
    A single (non-OR) Zlib license — the permissive Zlib license binds.
    Pulled in under flate2's `zlib-rs` backend (docx/xlsx/epub DEFLATE).
- ring           Apache-2.0 AND ISC
    The TLS stack's cryptography (via ureq → rustls, the link.md client
    verbs). The `ISC` term is CONJUNCTIVE — it always binds alongside
    Apache-2.0 (ring is a BoringSSL derivative whose new code is ISC).
- rustls-webpki  ISC
    X.509 path validation for rustls. A single (non-OR) ISC license binds.
- untrusted      ISC
    ring's untrusted-input parsing helper. A single ISC license binds.
- webpki-roots   CDLA-Permissive-2.0
    The bundled Mozilla/CCADB root-certificate DATA rustls verifies TLS
    against — a permissive *data* license (no copyleft, no patent traps);
    § 2.1 requires the agreement text travel with shared copies, so it is
    reproduced in the attribution section below.

All other shipped crates resolve to MIT and/or Apache-2.0 (often as one
branch of an `OR` expression alongside BSD/0BSD/Zlib/BSL-1.0/ISC
alternatives, which we discharge via the MIT/Apache branch).

