EPUB crate choice — license exclusion: the popular `epub` crate is
GPL-3.0, which violates this toolkit's permissive-only policy, so it is
NOT used. EPUB is a ZIP whose OPF package declares a reading-order spine
of XHTML documents; `dbmd` reads it with `zip` + `quick-xml` (container →
OPF → spine) and flattens each chapter with `html2text` — all already
present and all MIT. Same result, no GPL.

DOCX crate choice: `docx-rs` was an option, but `quick-xml` is already a
dependency (for EPUB) and `.docx` text is just the `<w:t>` runs of
`word/document.xml`; reading them directly avoids a second XML/zip stack.

PDF fallback (noted, not taken): if `pdf-extract` quality regresses, the
plan permits swapping to `pdfium-render` + `bblanchon/pdfium-binaries`
(BSD-3-Clause). That remains permissive-compliant; it is not in the tree
today.

YAML crate choice: `serde_norway` (a maintained `serde_yaml` fork).
`serde_yaml` is archived/deprecated upstream, and the previously-used
`serde_yml` plus its `libyml` backend were both flagged unsound and
unmaintained (RUSTSEC-2025-0068 / RUSTSEC-2025-0067). `serde_norway` and
its `unsafe-libyaml-norway` backend carry no open advisories. Same
MIT OR Apache-2.0 license.

The link.md client transport (the `linkmd` module — the `resolve` / `sync`
/ `grant` / `propose` / `subscribe` verbs; cargo feature `link`, default-on,
dropped by `default-features = false`). Deterministic transport plumbing
only: no AI/LLM, no telemetry, no auto-update — network I/O happens solely
when a verb is explicitly invoked against a user-configured hub.

- ureq             2.12.x   MIT OR Apache-2.0   — blocking HTTP client (no
                                                  async runtime), built with
                                                  default-features = false +
                                                  `tls` and `gzip` only. The
                                                  `tls` feature pulls the
                                                  rustls stack below; `gzip`
                                                  rides the flate2 already in
                                                  the tree
  (transitive: rustls `Apache-2.0 OR ISC OR MIT` — discharged via MIT;
   rustls-pki-types, base64, url/idna + the icu_* Unicode tables
   (MIT/Apache/Unicode-3.0, same obligations as unicode-ident above), log,
   once_cell — MIT OR Apache-2.0; subtle, zeroize — BSD-3-Clause /
   MIT-or-Apache; and the four call-outs above: ring `Apache-2.0 AND ISC`,
   rustls-webpki ISC, untrusted ISC, webpki-roots CDLA-Permissive-2.0)

TLS stack choice — license + portability: rustls with its `ring` provider
is the one stack that is (a) permissively licensed end to end, (b) free of
OpenSSL and system-TLS linkage so the released musl-static binaries carry
their own trust store on any distro, and (c) the same stack the wider Rust
CLI ecosystem ships. `aws-lc-rs` (the alternative provider) was excluded:
its `aws-lc-sys` build carries OpenSSL-license portions and a cmake/C
toolchain requirement, both of which this toolkit avoids.

